AN ACT relating to wildlife; [revising provisions governing the establishment of a
program which authorizes a person to transfer his or her tag to hunt a
big game mammal to any person who is under 18 years of age; revising
provisions relating to the exhibition or possession of certain licenses,
permits or related items while engaged in certain activities concerning
wildlife;] authorizing under certain circumstances a person to [take
or] gather shed antlers or a skull , [or] head or bones of a wildlife
species without a tag for non-commercial purposes; revising the
authority of the Board of Wildlife Commissioners to adopt
regulations relating to shed antlers; and providing other matters
properly relating thereto.
Legislative Counsel’s Digest:
1 [Existing law authorizes the Board of Wildlife Commissioners to adopt regulations
2 establishing a program that allows a person to transfer his or her tag to hunt a big game
3 mammal to any person who is under 18 years of age. (NRS 502.102) Section 1 of this bill
4 makes the adoption of the regulations mandatory.
5 Under existing law, a person is guilty of a misdemeanor if the person: (1) is required to
6 have a license or permit to engage in activities regulated by the provisions relating to wildlife;
7 and (2) while engaged in any such activity, refuses, upon the demand of an officer authorized
8 to enforce the fish and game laws of this State, to exhibit the license or permit, any wildlife in
9 the person’s possession or any weapon, ammunition, device or apparatus in the person’s
10 possession that may be used for any such activity. (NRS 502.120) Under existing law, this
11 crime is punishable by: (1) a fine of not less than $50 nor more than $500; (2) imprisonment
12 in the county jail for not more than 6 months; or (3) both fine and imprisonment. (NRS
13 501.385) Section 2 of this bill eliminates the criminal penalty for refusing to exhibit any of the
14 items other than the license or permit.
15 Subject to the same criminal penalty, a person is also guilty of a misdemeanor under
16 existing law if the person: (1) is required to have a license or permit to engage in activities
17 regulated by the provisions relating to wildlife; and (2) while engaged in any such activity,
18 fails to have the license or permit in his or her possession. (NRS 502.120) Section 2 clarifies
19 that, for purposes of this crime, the license or permit may be possessed in physical or
20 electronic form.]
21 In addition to regular licenses or permits to hunt, fish or trap, existing law provides for
22 additional licenses, known as tags, to hunt, trap or fish designated species of wildlife. (NRS

